Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and conditionally cancel it:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and handle the Shell toolbar back button via `BackButtonBehavior`:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    // Handles Android hardware/gesture back
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            ShowConfirmDialog();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async void ShowConfirmDialog()
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button (XAML):**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    BackCommand = new Command(OnBackRequested);
}

private async void OnBackRequested()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!leave) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` → Android/device back; return `true` to cancel.
- `BackButtonBehavior` → replaces the Shell toolbar arrow; `TextOverride` sets the label, `Command` routes through your confirmation logic.
- Both paths funnel through the same confirmation dialog and use `GoToAsync("..")` to navigate back only when confirmed.
